    <title>Open Design Engine - Feature #106 (New): Ability to Collapse Subprojects List</title>
    <link rel="alternate" href="http://opendesignengine.net/issues/106"/>
    <id>http://opendesignengine.net/issues/106</id>
    <updated>2013-01-13T23:00:14+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Jeremy Wright</name>
    </author>
    <content type="html">
&lt;p&gt;The Projects page would be cleaned up considerably if the sub-projects listed under each main project could be collapsed. It would be similar to the way sub-directories are listed in a file manager program on Linux, Windows, or MacOS, and can be collapsed so that you only see the parent directory.&lt;/p&gt;    </content>
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <title>Open Design Engine - Feature #104 (New): Allow Users to Accept or Reject Project "Invitations"</title>
    <link rel="alternate" href="http://opendesignengine.net/issues/104"/>
    <id>http://opendesignengine.net/issues/104</id>
    <updated>2013-01-06T12:22:39+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Jeremy Wright</name>
    </author>
    <content type="html">
&lt;p&gt;I was added to a project today by someone else, and it got me thinking. There's no confirmation that I've ever seen when you're added to a project, and you don't get a chance to decline the invitation. That means you could be added to a project unknowingly, even a project that you don't want to be associated with, without your knowledge or warning. This isn't a big deal now, but if/when ODE grows into the SoureForge of the hardware world, it may become an issue.&lt;/p&gt;    </content>
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <title>Open Design Engine - Feature #21 (New): Project assistance Bounty System</title>
    <link rel="alternate" href="http://opendesignengine.net/issues/21"/>
    <id>http://opendesignengine.net/issues/21</id>
    <updated>2011-04-09T16:11:58+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>J. Simmons</name>
    </author>
    <content type="html">
&lt;p&gt;mash up of craigslist, sourceforge, rent-a-coder, and a solution archive. The ideas is to have a website where "customers" can post discrete analysis, report writing, peer review, hardware build, component design requests, etc. &#8211; see &lt;a class="external" href="http://mach30.org/blogs/jrs/2009-10-22-ispcs-2009-day-1-mission-and-methods"&gt;http://mach30.org/blogs/jrs/2009-10-22-ispcs-2009-day-1-mission-and-methods&lt;/a&gt; for details. This is an attempt to discretize hardware development like wiki has discretized encyclopedia writing, enabling users to hop into a project to answer a specific need.&lt;/p&gt;    </content>
  </entry>
